# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: waveguides
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:waveguides/circulator] In electrical engineering, a **circulator** is a passive, non-reciprocal three- or four-port device that only allows a microwave or radio-frequency (RF) signal to exit through the port directly after the one it entered.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Optical circulators have similar behavior.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Ports are where an external waveguide or transmission line, such as a microstrip line or a coaxial cable, connects to the device.
[src:waveguides/circulator] For a three-port circulator, a signal applied to port 1 only comes out of port 2; a signal applied to port 2 only comes out of port 3; a signal applied to port 3 only comes out of port 1.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Microwave circulators rely on the anisotropic and *non-reciprocal* properties of magnetized microwave ferrite material.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Microwave electromagnetic waves propagating in magnetized ferrite interact with electron spins in the ferrite and are consequently influenced by the microwave magnetic permeability of the ferrite.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This permeability is mathematically described by a linear vector operator, also known as a tensor.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In the case of magnetized ferrite, the permeability tensor is the Polder tensor.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The permeability is a function of the direction of microwave propagation relative to the direction of static magnetization of the ferrite material.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Hence, microwave signals propagating in different directions in the ferrite experience different magnetic permeabilities.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In junction circulators and differential phase shift circulators, microwave signal propagation is usually orthogonal to the static magnetic bias field in the ferrite.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This is the so-called *transverse field* case.
[src:waveguides/circulator] where $\mu _{0}$ is the permeability of free space and $\epsilon$ is the absolute permittivity of the ferrite material.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In a circulator, these propagation constants describe waves having elliptical polarization that would propagate in the direction of the static magnetic bias field, which is through the thickness of the ferrite.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The plus and minus subscripts of the propagation constants indicate opposite wave polarizations.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Microwave circulators fall into two main classes: differential phase shift circulators and junction circulators, both of which are based on cancellation of waves propagating over two different paths in or near magnetized ferrite material.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Waveguide circulators may be of either type, while more compact devices based on stripline are usually of the junction type.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Two or more junction circulators can be combined in a single component to give four or more ports.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Typically permanent magnets produce a static magnetic bias in the microwave ferrite material.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Ferrimagnetic garnet crystal is used in optical circulators.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A stripline junction circulator contains a resonator, which is located at the central junction of the striplines.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This resonator may have any shape that has three-fold Rotational symmetry, such as a disk, hexagon, or triangle.
[src:waveguides/circulator] An RF/microwave signal entering a circulator port is connected via a stripline to the resonator, where energy is coupled into two counter-rotating circular modes formed by the elliptically polarized waves.
[src:waveguides/circulator] These circular modes have different phase velocities which can cause them to combine constructively or destructively at a given port.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This produces an anti-node at one port (port 2 if the signal is incident upon port 1) and a node or null at another port (port 3 if the microwave energy is coupled from port 1 to port 2 and not reflected back into port 2).
[src:waveguides/circulator] where l is the path length between adjacent ports and m and n are integers.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Each of the two counter-rotating modes has its own resonant frequency.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The two resonant frequencies are known as the split frequencies.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The circulator operating frequency is set between the two split frequencies.
[src:waveguides/circulator] These circulator types operate based on faraday rotation.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Wave cancellation occurs when waves propagate with and against the circulator's direction of circulation.
[src:waveguides/circulator] An incident wave arriving at any port is split equally into two waves.
[src:waveguides/circulator] They propagate in each direction around the circulator with different phase velocities.
[src:waveguides/circulator] When they arrive at the output port they have different phase relationships and thus combine accordingly.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This combination of waves propagating at different phase velocities is how junction circulators fundamentally operate.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The geometry of a stripline junction circulator comprises two ferrite disks or triangles separated by a stripline center conductor and sandwiched between two parallel ground planes.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A stripline circulator is essentially a stripline center conductor sandwich on ferrite, between ground planes.
[src:waveguides/circulator] That is, there is one ferrite disk above the stripline circuit and one ferrite disk below the stripline circuit.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Stripline circulators do not have to be constructed with disk- or triangle-shaped ferrites; the ferrites can have almost any shape that has three-way symmetry.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This is also true of the resonator (the center junction portion of the center conductor)- it can be any shape that has three-way symmetry, although there are electrical considerations.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The ferrites are magnetized through their thicknesses, i.e., the static magnetic bias field is perpendicular to the plane of the device and the direction of signal propagation is transverse to the direction of the static magnetic field.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Both ferrites are in the same static ad RF magnetic fields.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The two ferrites can be thought of as one continuous ferrite with an embedded stripline center conductor.
[src:waveguides/circulator] For practical manufacturing reasons, the center conductor is not generally embedded in ferrite, so two discrete ferrites are used.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The static magnetic bias field is typically provided by permanent magnets that are located external to the circulator ground planes.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Magnetic shielding incorporated into the circulator design prevents detuning or partial demagnetization of the circulator in the presence of external magnetic fields or ferrous materials, and protects nearby devices from the effects of the circulator's static magnetic field.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A waveguide junction circulator contains a magnetized ferrite resonator, which is located at the junction of three waveguides.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In contrast with a stripline junction circulator, the ferrite itself is the resonator, rather than the metal central portion of a stripline center conductor.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The ferrite resonator may have any shape that has three-fold rotational symmetry, such as a cylinder or triangular prism.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The resonator is often just one ferrite, but it is sometimes composed of two or more ferrites, which may be coupled to each other, in various geometrical configurations.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The geometry of the resonator is influenced by electrical and thermal performance considerations.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Waveguide junction circulators function in much the same way as stripline junction circulators, and their basic theory of operation is the same.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The internal geometry of a waveguide junction circulator comprises a junction of three waveguides, the ferrite resonator, and impedance matching structures.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Many of these circulators contain pedestals located in the central junction, on which the ferrite resonator is located.
[src:waveguides/circulator] These pedestals effectively reduce the height of the waveguide, reducing its characteristic impedance in the resonator region to optimize electrical performance.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The reduced-height waveguide sections leading from the resonator to the full-height waveguides serve as impedance transformers.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The ferrite resonator is magnetized through its height, i.e., the static magnetic bias field is perpendicular to the plane of the device and the direction of signal propagation is transverse to the direction of the static magnetic field.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The static magnetic bias field is typically provided by permanent magnets that are external to the waveguide junction.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The microstrip junction circulator is another widely used form of circulator that utilizes the microstrip transmission line topology.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A microstrip circulator consists primarily of a circuit pattern on a ferrite substrate.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The circuit is typically formed using thick-film or thin-film metallization processes, often including photolithography.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A permanent magnet that is bonded to the circuit face of the ferrite substrate provides the static magnetic bias to the ferrite.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Microstrip circulators function in the same way as stripline junction circulators, and their basic theory of operation is the same.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In comparison with stripline circulators, electrical performance of microstrip circulators is somewhat reduced because of radiation and dispersion effects.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The performance disadvantages of microstrip circulators are offset by their relative ease of integration with other planar circuitry.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The electrical connections of these circulators to adjacent circuitry are typically made using wire bonds or ribbon bonds.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Another advantage of microstrip circulators is their smaller size and correspondingly lower mass than stripline circulators.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Despite this advantage, microstrip circulators are often the largest components in microwave modules.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Self-biased junction circulators are unique in that they do not utilize permanent magnets that are separate from the microwave ferrite.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The elimination of external magnets significantly reduces the size and weight of the circulator compared to electrically-equivalent microstrip junction circulators for similar applications.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Monolithic ferrites that are used for self-biased circulators are M-type uniaxial (single magnetic axis) hexagonal ferrites that have been optimized to have low microwave losses.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In contrast with the magnetically soft (low-coercivity) ferrites used in other circulators, the hexagonal ferrites used for self-biased circulators are magnetically hard (high-coercivity) materials.
[src:waveguides/circulator] These ferrites are essentially ceramic permanent magnets.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In addition to their high magnetic remanence, these ferrites have very large magnetic anisotropy fields, enabling circulator operation up to high microwave frequencies.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Because of their thin, planar shape, self-biased circulators can be conveniently integrated with other planar circuitry.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Integration of self-biased circulators with semiconductor wafers has been demonstrated at KA-band and V-band frequencies.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Lumped-element circulators are small-size devices that are typically used at frequencies in the HF through UHF bands.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In a junction circulator, the size of the ferrite(s) is proportional to signal wavelength, but in a lumped-element circulator, the ferrite can be smaller because there is no such wavelength proportionality.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In a lumped-element circulator, conductors are wrapped around the ferrite, forming what is typically a woven mesh.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The conductor strips are insulated from each other by thin dielectric layers.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In some circulators, the mesh is in the form of traces on a printed wiring board with metallized vias to make connections between layers.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The conductive strips can be thought of as non-reciprocally coupled inductors.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Impedance matching circuitry and broad-banding circuitry in lumped-element circulators are often constructed using discrete ceramic capacitors and air-core inductors.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This class of circulator offers a considerable size reduction compared with the junction circulators.
[src:waveguides/circulator] On the other hand, lumped-element circulators generally have lower RF power handling capacity than equivalent junction devices and are more complex from a mechanical perspective.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The discrete lumped-element inductors and capacitors can be less stable when exposed to vibration or mechanical shocks than the simple distributed impedance transformers in a stripline junction circulator.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Switching circulators are similar to other junction circulators, and their microwave theory of operation is the same, except that their direction of circulation can be electronically controlled.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Junction circulators use permanent magnets to provide the static magnetic bias for the ferrite(s).
[src:waveguides/circulator] However, switching circulators typically rely on the remanent magnetization of the ferrite itself.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The ferrites that are used in switching circulators have square magnetic hysteresis loops and often sub-Oersted coercivities.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Such a ferrite material requires a relatively small magnetic field and low energy level to flip its magnetic polarity.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The magnetization polarity of the ferrite, and hence the direction of circulation of a switching circulator, is controlled using a magnetizing coil that loops through the ferrite.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The coil is connected to electronic driver circuitry that sends current pulses of the correct polarity through the magnetizing coil to magnetize the ferrite in the polarity to provide the desired direction of circulation.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Differential phase shift circulators are mainly used in high power microwave applications.
[src:waveguides/circulator] They are usually built from rectangular waveguide components.
[src:waveguides/circulator] These circulators are 4-port devices having circulation in the sequence 1 - 2 - 3 - 4 - 1, with ports numbered as shown in the schematic.
[src:waveguides/circulator] There are various feasible circulator architectures, the most common of which utilizes a magic tee hybrid coupler, a quadrature hybrid coupler, and two oppositely magnetized differential phase shifters.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A differential phase shifter provides *non-reciprocal* transmission phase shift.
[src:waveguides/circulator] That is, the forward phase shift is different from the phase shift in the reverse transmission direction.
[src:waveguides/circulator] It is this difference in phase shifts that enables the non-reciprocal behavior of the circulator.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A differential phase shifter consists of one or more ferrite slabs, usually positioned on the broad wall(s) of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Permanent magnets located outside the waveguide provide static magnetic bias field to the ferrite(s).
[src:waveguides/circulator] The ferrite-loaded waveguide is another example of a *transverse-field* device as described in Circulator § Theory of operation.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Different microwave propagation constants corresponding to different directions of signal propagation give rise to different phase velocities and hence, different transmission phase shifts.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Depending on which circulator port an incident signal enters, phase shift relationships in the hybrid couplers and the differential phase shifts cause signals to combine at one other port and cancel at each of the remaining two ports.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Differential phase shift circulators are often used as 3-port circulators by connecting one circulator port to a reflectionless termination, or they can be used as isolators by terminating two circulator ports.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Though ferrite circulators can provide good "forward" signal circulation while suppressing greatly the "reverse" circulation, their major shortcomings, especially at low frequencies, are the bulky sizes and the narrow bandwidths.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Early work on non-ferrite circulators includes active circulators using transistors that are non-reciprocal in nature.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In contrast to ferrite circulators which are passive devices, active circulators require power.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Major issues associated with transistor-based active circulators are the power limitation and the signal-to-noise degradation, which are critical when it is used as a duplexer for sustaining the strong transmit power and clean reception of the signal from the antenna.
[src:waveguides/circulator] One study employed a structure similar to a time-varying transmission line with the effective nonreciprocity triggered by a one-direction propagating carrier pump.
[src:waveguides/circulator] This is like an AC-powered active circulator.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The research claimed to be able to achieve positive gain and low noise for receiving path and broadband nonreciprocity.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Another study used resonance with nonreciprocity triggered by angular-momentum biasing, which more closely mimics the way that signals passively circulate in a ferrite circulator.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In 1964, Mohr presented and experimentally demonstrated a circulator based on transmission lines and switches.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In April, 2016 a research team significantly extended this concept, presenting an integrated circuit circulator based on N-path filter concepts.
[src:waveguides/circulator] It offers the potential for full-duplex communication (transmitting and receiving at the same time with a single shared antenna over a single frequency).
[src:waveguides/circulator] The device uses capacitors and a clock and is much smaller than conventional devices.
[src:waveguides/circulator] When one port of a three-port circulator is terminated in a matched load, it can be used as an *isolator*, since a signal can travel in only one direction between the remaining ports.
[src:waveguides/circulator] An isolator is used to shield equipment on its input side from the effects of conditions on its output side; for example, to prevent a microwave source being detuned by a mismatched load.
[src:waveguides/circulator] In radar, circulators are used as a type of duplexer, to route signals from the transmitter to the antenna and from the antenna to the receiver, without allowing signals to pass directly from transmitter to receiver.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The alternative type of duplexer is a *transmit-receive switch* (*TR switch*) that alternates between connecting the antenna to the transmitter and to the receiver.
[src:waveguides/circulator] The use of chirped pulses and a high dynamic range may lead to temporal overlap of the sent and received pulses, however, requiring a circulator for this function.
[src:waveguides/circulator] A reflection amplifier is a type of microwave amplifier circuit utilizing negative differential resistance diodes such as tunnel diodes and Gunn diodes.
[src:waveguides/circulator] Negative differential resistance diodes can amplify signals, and often perform better at microwave frequencies than two-port devices.
[src:waveguides/circulator] However, since the diode is a one-port (two terminal) device, a nonreciprocal component is needed to separate the outgoing amplified signal from the incoming input signal.
[src:waveguides/circulator] By using a 3-port circulator with the signal input connected to one port, the biased diode connected to a second, and the output load connected to the third, the output and input can be uncoupled.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In physics and electrical engineering, a **cutoff frequency**, **corner frequency**, or **break frequency** is a boundary in a system's frequency response at which energy flowing through the system begins to be reduced (attenuated or reflected) rather than passing through.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Typically in electronic systems such as filters and communication channels, cutoff frequency applies to an edge in a lowpass, highpass, bandpass, or band-stop characteristic – a frequency characterizing a boundary between a passband and a stopband.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] It is sometimes taken to be the point in the filter response where a transition band and passband meet, for example, as defined by a **half-power bandwidth** (or half-power point), a frequency for which the output of the circuit is approximately −3.01 dB of the nominal passband value.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Alternatively, a stopband corner frequency may be specified as a point where a transition band and a stopband meet: a frequency for which the attenuation is larger than the required stopband attenuation, which for example may be 30 dB or 100 dB.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In the case of a waveguide or an antenna, the cutoff frequencies correspond to the lower and upper **cutoff wavelengths**.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In electronics, cutoff frequency or corner frequency is the frequency either above or below which the power output of a circuit, such as a line, amplifier, or electronic filter has fallen to a given proportion of the power in the passband.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Most frequently this proportion is one half the passband power, also referred to as the 3 dB point since a fall of 3 dB corresponds approximately to half power.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] As a voltage ratio this is a fall to ${\textstyle {\sqrt {1/2}}\ \approx \ 0.707}$ of the passband voltage.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The **half-power bandwidth** is a commonly used definition for the cutoff frequency.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] This occurs when the output voltage has dropped to ${\tfrac {1}{\sqrt {2}}}\approx {\text{0.707}}$ of the filter's nominal passband voltage and the power has dropped by half.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] A bandpass amplifier will have two half-power points, while a low-pass amplifier or a high-pass amplifier will have only one.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The bandwidth of a filter or amplifier is usually defined as the difference between the lower and upper half-power points.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] This is, therefore, also known as the 3 dB bandwidth.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] There is no lower half-power point for a low-pass amplifier, so the bandwidth is measured relative to DC, i.e., 0 Hz.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] There is no upper half-power point for an ideal high-pass amplifier, its bandwidth is theoretically infinite.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In practice the stopband and transition band are used to characterize a high-pass.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Other ratios besides the 3 dB point may also be relevant, for example see § Chebyshev filters below.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Far from the cutoff frequency in the transition band, the rate of increase of attenuation (roll-off) with logarithm of frequency is asymptotic to a constant.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The transfer function for the simplest low-pass filter, $H(s)={\frac {1}{1+\alpha s}},$ has a single pole at *s* = −1/*α*.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Where s is the s-plane variable, ω is angular frequency and *j* is the imaginary unit.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Sometimes other ratios are more convenient than the 3 dB point.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] For instance, in the case of the Chebyshev filter it is usual to define the cutoff frequency as the point after the last peak in the frequency response at which the level has fallen to the design value of the passband ripple.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The amount of ripple in this class of filter can be set by the designer to any desired value, hence the ratio used could be any value.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In radio communication, skywave communication is a technique in which radio waves are transmitted at an angle into the sky and reflected back to Earth by layers of charged particles in the ionosphere.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In this context, the term *cutoff frequency* refers to the maximum usable frequency, the frequency above which a radio wave fails to reflect off the ionosphere at the incidence angle required for transmission between two specified points by reflection from the layer.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The cutoff frequency of an electromagnetic waveguide is the lowest frequency for which a mode will propagate in it.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In fiber optics, it is more common to consider the **cutoff wavelength**, the maximum wavelength that will propagate in an optical fiber or waveguide.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The cutoff frequency is found with the characteristic equation of the Helmholtz equation for electromagnetic waves, which is derived from the electromagnetic wave equation by setting the longitudinal wave number equal to zero and solving for the frequency.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] Thus, any exciting frequency lower than the cutoff frequency will attenuate, rather than propagate.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The following derivation assumes lossless walls.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The value of c, the speed of light, should be taken to be the group velocity of light in whatever material fills the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] For a rectangular waveguide, the cutoff frequency is $\omega _{c}=c{\sqrt {\left({\frac {m\pi }{a}}\right)^{2}+\left({\frac {n\pi }{b}}\right)^{2}}},$ where $m,n\geq 0$ are the mode numbers for the rectangle's sides of length a and b respectively.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] For TE modes, $m,n\geq 0$ (but $m=n=0$ is not allowed), while for TM modes $m,n\geq 1$ .
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] However, the dominant mode cutoff frequency can be reduced by the introduction of baffle inside the circular cross-section waveguide.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] For a single-mode optical fiber, the cutoff wavelength is the wavelength at which the normalized frequency is approximately equal to 2.405.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] It is a property of all the eigenmodes of the electromagnetic waveguide that at least one of the two fields is transverse.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The *z* axis is defined to be along the axis of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The final step depends on the geometry of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The easiest geometry to solve is the rectangular waveguide.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] The cutoff frequency $\omega _{c}$ is the critical frequency between propagation and attenuation, which corresponds to the frequency at which the longitudinal wavenumber $k_{z}$ is zero.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] It is given by $\omega _{c}=c{\sqrt {\left({\frac {n\pi }{a}}\right)^{2}+\left({\frac {m\pi }{b}}\right)^{2}}}$ The wave equations are also valid below the cutoff frequency, where the longitudinal wave number is imaginary.
[src:waveguides/cutoff-frequency] In this case, the field decays exponentially along the waveguide axis and the wave is thus evanescent.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] An **optical waveguide** is a physical structure that guides electromagnetic waves in the optical spectrum.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Common types of optical waveguides include optical fiber waveguides, transparent dielectric waveguides made of plastic and glass, liquid light guides, and liquid waveguides.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical waveguides are used as components in integrated optical circuits or as the transmission medium in local and long-haul optical communication systems.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] They can also be used in optical head-mounted displays in augmented reality.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical waveguides can be classified according to their geometry (planar, strip, or fiber waveguides), mode structure (single-mode, multi-mode), refractive index distribution (step or gradient index), and material (glass, polymer, semiconductor).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The basic principles behind optical waveguides can be described using the concepts of geometrical or ray optics, as illustrated in the diagram.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Light passing into a medium with higher refractive index bends toward the normal by the process of refraction (Figure **a.**).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Take, for example, light passing from air into glass.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Similarly, light traveling in the opposite direction (from glass into air) takes the same path, bending away from the normal.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] This is a consequence of time-reversal symmetry.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Each ray in air (black) can be mapped to a ray in the glass (blue), as shown in Figure **b**.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] But because of refraction, some of the rays in the glass are left out (red).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The remaining rays are trapped in the glass by a process called *total internal reflection*.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] They are incident on the glass-air interface at an angle above the *critical angle*.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] These extra rays correspond to a higher *density of states* in more-advanced formulations based on the Green's function.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Using total internal reflection, light can be trapped and guided in a dielectric waveguide (Figure **c**).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The red rays bounce off both the top and bottom surface of the high index medium.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] They're guided even if the slab curves or bends, so long as it bends slowly.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] This is the basic principle behind fiber optics in which light is guided along a high index glass *core* in a lower index glass *cladding* (Figure **d**).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Ray optics only gives a rough picture of how waveguides work.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Maxwell's equations can be solved by analytical or numerical methods for a full-field description of a dielectric waveguide.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Perhaps the simplest optical waveguide is the dielectric **slab waveguide**, also called a **planar waveguide**.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Owing to their simplicity, slab waveguides are often used as toy models but also find application in on-chip devices like arrayed waveguide gratings and acousto-optic filters and modulators.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The slab waveguide consists of three layers of materials with different dielectric constants, extending infinitely in the directions parallel to their interfaces.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Light is confined in the middle layer by total internal reflection if the refractive index of the middle layer is larger than that of the surrounding layers.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The slab waveguide is essentially a one-dimensional waveguide.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] It traps light only normal to the dielectric interfaces.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] For guided modes, the field in domain II in the diagram is propagating and can be treated as a plane wave.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The field in domains I and III evanescently decay away from the slab.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The plane wave in domain II bounces between the top and bottom interfaces at some angle typically specified by the ${\vec {\beta }}$ , the wave vector in the plane of the slab.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Guided modes constructively interfere on one complete roundtrip in the slab.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] At each frequency, one or more modes can be found giving a set of eigenvalues $(\omega ,{\vec {\beta }})$ which can be used to construct a band diagram or dispersion relation.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Because guided modes are trapped in the slab, they cannot be excited by light incident on the top or bottom interfaces.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Light can be *end-fire or butte coupled* by injecting it with a lens in the plane of the slab.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Alternatively a coupling element may be used to couple light into the waveguide, such as a grating coupler or prism coupler.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] There are two technologies: diffractive waveguides and reflective waveguides.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] A **strip waveguide** is basically a strip of the layer confined between cladding layers.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The simplest case is a **rectangular waveguide**, which is formed when the guiding layer of the slab waveguide is restricted in both transverse directions rather than just one.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Rectangular waveguides are used in integrated optical circuits and in laser diodes.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] They are commonly used as the basis of such optical components as Mach–Zehnder interferometers and wavelength division multiplexers.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The cavities of laser diodes are frequently constructed as rectangular optical waveguides.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical waveguides with rectangular geometry are produced by a variety of means, usually by a planar process.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The field distribution in a rectangular waveguide cannot be solved analytically, however approximate solution methods, such as Marcatili's method, Extended Marcatili's method and Kumar's method, are known.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] A **rib waveguide** is a waveguide in which the guiding layer basically consists of the slab with a strip (or several strips) superimposed onto it.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Rib waveguides also provide confinement of the wave in two dimensions and near-unity confinement is possible in multi-layer rib structures.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical waveguides typically maintain a constant cross-section along their direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] This is for example the case for strip and of rib waveguides.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] However, waveguides can also have periodic changes in their cross-section while still allowing lossless transmission of light via so-called Bloch modes.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Such waveguides are referred to as segmented waveguides (with a 1D patterning along the direction of propagation) or as photonic crystal waveguides (with a 2D or 3D patterning).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical waveguides find their most important application in photonics.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Configuring the waveguides in 3D space provides integration between electronic components on a chip and optical fibers.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Such waveguides may be designed for a single mode propagation of infrared light at telecommunication wavelengths, and configured to deliver optical signal between input and output locations with very low loss.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] One of the methods for constructing such waveguides utilizes photorefractive effect in transparent materials.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] An increase in the refractive index of a material may be induced by nonlinear absorption of pulsed laser light.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] In order to maximize the increase of the refractive index, a very short (typically femtosecond) laser pulses are used, and focused with a high NA microscope objective.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] By translating the focal spot through a bulk transparent material the waveguides can be directly written.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] A variation of this method uses a low NA microscope objective and translates the focal spot along the beam axis.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] This improves the overlap between the focused laser beam and the photorefractive material, thus reducing power needed from the laser.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] When transparent material is exposed to an unfocused laser beam of sufficient brightness to initiate photorefractive effect, the waveguides may start forming on their own as a result of an accumulated self-focusing.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] The formation of such waveguides leads to a breakup of the laser beam.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Continued exposure results in a buildup of the refractive index towards the centerline of each waveguide, and collapse of the mode field diameter of the propagating light.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Such waveguides remain permanently in the glass and can be photographed off-line (see the picture on the right).
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Light pipes are tubes or cylinders of solid material used to guide light a short distance.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] In electronics, plastic light pipes are used to guide light from LEDs on a circuit board to the user interface surface.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] In buildings, light pipes are used to transfer illumination from outside the building to where it is needed inside.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical fiber is typically a circular cross-section *dielectric waveguide* consisting of a dielectric material surrounded by another dielectric material with a lower refractive index.
[src:waveguides/rectangular-waveguide] Optical fibers are most commonly made from silica glass, however other glass materials are used for certain applications and plastic optical fiber can be used for short-distance applications.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] A **transverse mode** of electromagnetic radiation is a particular electromagnetic field pattern of the radiation in the plane perpendicular (i.e., transverse) to the radiation's propagation direction.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Transverse modes occur in radio waves and microwaves confined to a waveguide, and also in light waves in an optical fiber and in a laser's optical resonator.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Transverse modes occur because of boundary conditions imposed on the wave by the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] For example, a radio wave in a hollow metal waveguide must have zero tangential electric field amplitude at the walls of the waveguide, so the transverse pattern of the electric field of waves is restricted to those that fit between the walls.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] For this reason, the modes supported by a waveguide are quantized.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The allowed modes can be found by solving Maxwell's equations for the boundary conditions of a given waveguide.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Unguided electromagnetic waves in free space, or in a bulk isotropic dielectric, can be described as a superposition of plane waves; these can be described as TEM modes as defined below.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] However in any sort of waveguide where boundary conditions are imposed by a physical structure, a wave of a particular frequency can be described in terms of a transverse mode (or superposition of such modes).
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] These modes generally follow different propagation constants.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Neither electric nor magnetic field in the direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] No electric field in the direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] is the conventional symbol for magnetic field).
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] No magnetic field in the direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] because there is only an electric field along the direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Non-zero electric and magnetic fields in the direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In coaxial cable energy is normally transported in the fundamental TEM mode.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The TEM mode is also usually assumed for most other electrical conductor line formats as well.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] This is mostly an accurate assumption, but a major exception is microstrip which has a significant longitudinal component to the propagated wave due to the inhomogeneity at the boundary of the dielectric substrate below the conductor and the air above it.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Inhomogeneity also occurs at connectors or bends in a coaxial cable.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Non-TEM modes created by connectors are usually negligible unless the signal has a high enough frequency.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] This is referred to as maximum **extraneous-mode-free operation** or simply **mode-free operation** frequency of the connector.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In an optical fiber or other dielectric waveguide, modes are generally of the hybrid type.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Hollow metallic waveguides filled with a homogeneous, isotropic material (usually air) support TE and TM modes but not the TEM mode.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In circular waveguides, circular modes exist and here *m* is the number of full-wave patterns along the circumference and *n* is the number of half-wave patterns along the diameter.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The number of modes in an optical fiber distinguishes multi-mode optical fiber from single-mode optical fiber.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] To determine the number of modes in a step-index fiber, the V number needs to be determined: ${\textstyle V=k_{0}a{\sqrt {n_{1}^{2}-n_{2}^{2}}}}$ where $k_{0}$ is the wavenumber, a is the fiber's core radius, and $n_{1}$ and $n_{2}$ are the refractive indices of the core and cladding, respectively.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Fiber with a V-parameter of less than 2.405 only supports the fundamental mode (a hybrid mode), and is therefore a single-mode fiber whereas fiber with a higher V-parameter has multiple modes.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Decomposition of field distributions into modes is useful because a large number of field amplitudes readings can be simplified into a much smaller number of mode amplitudes.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Because these modes change over time according to a simple set of rules, it is also possible to anticipate future behavior of the field distribution.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] These simplifications of complex field distributions ease the signal processing requirements of fiber-optic communication systems.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The modes in typical low refractive index contrast fibers are usually referred to as *LP* (linear polarization) modes, which refers to a scalar approximation for the field solution, treating it as if it contains only one transverse field component.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In a laser with cylindrical symmetry, the transverse mode patterns are described by a combination of a Gaussian beam profile with a Laguerre polynomial.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The modes are denoted TEM*pl* where p and l are integers labeling the radial and angular mode orders, respectively.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] With *p* = *l* = 0, the TEM00 mode is the lowest order.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] It is the fundamental transverse mode of the laser resonator and has the same form as a Gaussian beam.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The pattern has a single lobe, and has a constant phase across the mode.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Modes with increasing p show concentric rings of intensity, and modes with increasing l show angularly distributed lobes.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In general there are 2*l*(*p*+1) spots in the mode pattern (except for *l* = 0).
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The TEM0*i** mode, the so-called *doughnut mode*, is a special case consisting of a superposition of two TEM0*i* modes (*i* = 1, 2, 3), rotated 360°/4*i* with respect to one another.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The overall size of the mode is determined by the Gaussian beam radius w, and this may increase or decrease with the propagation of the beam, however the modes preserve their general shape during propagation.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Higher order modes are relatively larger compared to the TEM00 mode, and thus the fundamental Gaussian mode of a laser may be selected by placing an appropriately sized aperture in the laser cavity.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In many lasers, the symmetry of the optical resonator is restricted by polarizing elements such as Brewster's angle windows.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] In these lasers, transverse modes with rectangular symmetry are formed.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] These modes are designated TEM*mn* with m and n being the horizontal and vertical orders of the pattern.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The TEM00 mode corresponds to exactly the same fundamental mode as in the cylindrical geometry.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] Modes with increasing m and n show lobes appearing in the horizontal and vertical directions, with in general (*m* + 1)(*n* + 1) lobes present in the pattern.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] As before, higher-order modes have a larger spatial extent than the 00 mode.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The phase of each lobe of a TEM*mn* is offset by *π* radians with respect to its horizontal or vertical neighbours.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] This is equivalent to the polarization of each lobe being flipped in direction.
[src:waveguides/transverse-mode] The overall intensity profile of a laser's output may be made up from the superposition of any of the allowed transverse modes of the laser's cavity, though often it is desirable to operate only on the fundamental mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In radio-frequency engineering and communications engineering, a **waveguide** is a hollow metal pipe used to carry radio waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] This type of waveguide is used as a transmission line mostly at microwave frequencies, for such purposes as connecting microwave transmitters and receivers to their antennas, in equipment such as microwave ovens, radar sets, satellite communications, and microwave radio links.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The group velocity of guided electromagnetic waves (EMW) is a fraction of the speed of light.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Propagation in a (metal-pipe) waveguide may be imagined as a zig-zag path, with the EMW being repeatedly reflected between opposite walls of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For the particular case of **rectangular waveguide**, it is possible to base an exact analysis on this view.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Propagation in a dielectric waveguide may be viewed in the same way, with the waves confined to the dielectric by total internal reflection at its surface.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Some structures, such as non-radiative dielectric waveguides and the Goubau line, use both metal walls and dielectric surfaces to confine the wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Depending on the frequency, waveguides can be constructed from either conductive or dielectric materials.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Generally, the lower the frequency to be passed the larger the waveguide is.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For example, the natural waveguide the earth forms given by the dimensions between the conductive ionosphere and the ground as well as the circumference at the median altitude of the Earth is resonant at 7.83 Hz.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] On the other hand, waveguides used in extremely high frequency (EHF) communications can be less than a millimeter in width.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] During the 1890s, theorists did the first analyses of electromagnetic waves in ducts.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Thomson derived the electromagnetic modes inside a cylindrical metal cavity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In 1897, Lord Rayleigh did a definitive analysis of waveguides; he solved the boundary value problem of electromagnetic waves propagating through both conducting tubes and dielectric rods of arbitrary shape.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] He showed that the waves could travel without attenuation only in specific normal modes with either the electric field (TE modes) or magnetic field (TM modes), perpendicular to the direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] He also showed each mode had a cutoff frequency below which waves would not propagate.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Since the cutoff wavelength for a given tube was of the same order as its width, it was clear that a hollow conducting tube could not carry radio wavelengths much larger than its diameter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Weber observed that electromagnetic waves travel at a slower speed in tubes than in free space, and deduced the reason; that the waves travel in a "zigzag" path as they reflect from the walls.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Prior to the 1920s, practical work on radio waves concentrated on the low frequency end of the radio spectrum, as these frequencies were better for long-range communication.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] These were far below the frequencies that could propagate in even large waveguides, so there was little experimental work on waveguides during this period, although a few experiments were done.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In a June 1, 1894, lecture, "The work of Hertz", before the Royal Society, Oliver Lodge demonstrated the transmission of 3 inch radio waves from a spark gap through a short cylindrical copper duct.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In his pioneering 1894-1900 research on microwaves, Jagadish Chandra Bose used short lengths of pipe to conduct the waves, so some sources credit him with inventing the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] However, after this, the concept of radio waves being carried by a tube or duct passed out of engineering knowledge.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] During the 1920s, the first continuous sources of high frequency radio waves were developed: the Barkhausen–Kurz tube, the first oscillator which could produce power at UHF frequencies; and the split-anode magnetron which by the 1930s had generated radio waves at up to 10 GHz.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] These made possible the first systematic research on microwaves in the 1930s.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] It was discovered that transmission lines used to carry lower frequency radio waves, parallel line and coaxial cable, had excessive power losses at microwave frequencies, creating a need for a new transmission method.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The waveguide was developed independently between 1932 and 1936 by George C.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Southworth at Bell Telephone Laboratories and Wilmer L.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Barrow at the Massachusetts Institute of Technology, who worked without knowledge of one another.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Southworth's interest was sparked during his 1920s doctoral work in which he measured the dielectric constant of water with a radio frequency Lecher line in a long tank of water.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] He found that if he removed the Lecher line, the tank of water still showed resonance peaks, indicating it was acting as a dielectric waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] At Bell Labs in 1931, he resumed work in dielectric waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] By March 1932, he observed waves in water-filled copper pipes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Rayleigh's previous work had been forgotten, and Sergei A.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Schelkunoff, a Bell Labs mathematician, did theoretical analyses of waveguides and rediscovered waveguide modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In December 1933 it was realized that with a metal sheath the dielectric is superfluous and attention shifted to metal waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Barrow had become interested in high frequencies in 1930 studying under Arnold Sommerfeld in Germany.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] At MIT beginning in 1932, he worked on high frequency antennas to generate narrow beams of radio waves to locate aircraft in fog.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] He invented a horn antenna and hit on the idea of using a hollow pipe as a feedline to feed radio waves to the antenna.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] By March 1936, he had derived the propagation modes and cutoff frequency in a rectangular waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The source he was using had a large wavelength of 40 cm, so for his first successful waveguide experiments he used a 16-foot section of air duct, 18 inches in diameter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Barrow and Southworth became aware of each other's work a few weeks before both were scheduled to present papers on waveguides to a combined meeting of the American Physical Society and the Institute of Radio Engineers in May 1936.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] They amicably worked out credit sharing and patent division arrangements.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The development of centimeter radar during World War 2 and the first high power microwave tubes, the klystron (1938) and cavity magnetron (1940), resulted in the first widespread use of waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Standard waveguide plumbing-like components were manufactured, with flanges on the end which could be bolted together.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In the 1960s, waveguides became common in commercial microwave systems, such as airport radar and microwave relay networks which were built to transmit telephone calls and television programs between cities.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In the microwave region of the electromagnetic spectrum, a waveguide normally consists of a hollow metallic conductor.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] These waveguides can take the form of single conductors with or without a dielectric coating, e.g. the Goubau line and helical waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Hollow waveguides must be one-half wavelength or more in diameter in order to support one or more transverse wave modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Waveguides may be filled with pressurized gas to inhibit arcing and prevent multipaction, allowing higher power transmission.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Conversely, waveguides may be required to be evacuated as part of evacuated systems (e.g. electron beam systems).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] A slotted waveguide is generally used for radar and other similar applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The waveguide serves as a feed path, and each slot is a separate radiator, thus forming an antenna.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] This structure has the capability of generating a radiation pattern to launch an electromagnetic wave in a specific relatively narrow and controllable direction.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The dimensions of a hollow metallic waveguide determine which wavelengths it can support, and in which modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Typically, the waveguide is operated so that only a single mode is present.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The lowest order mode possible is generally selected.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Frequencies below the guide's cutoff frequency will not propagate.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] It is possible to operate waveguides at higher order modes, or with multiple modes present, but this is usually impractical.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Waveguides are almost exclusively made of metal and mostly rigid structures.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] There are certain types of "corrugated" waveguides that have the ability to flex and bend but only used where essential since they degrade propagation properties.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Due to propagation of energy in mostly air or space within the waveguide, it is one of the lowest loss transmission line types and highly preferred for high frequency applications where most other types of transmission structures introduce large losses.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Due to the skin effect at high frequencies, electric current along the walls penetrates typically only a few micrometers into the metal of the inner surface.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Since this is where most of the resistive loss occurs, it is important that the conductivity of interior surface be kept as high as possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For this reason, most waveguide interior surfaces are plated with copper, silver, or gold.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Voltage standing wave ratio (VSWR) measurements may be taken to ensure that a waveguide is contiguous and has no leaks or sharp bends.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] If such bends or holes in the waveguide surface are present, this may diminish the performance of both transmitter and receiver equipment connected at either end.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Poor transmission through the waveguide may also occur as a result of moisture build up which corrodes and degrades conductivity of the inner surfaces, which is crucial for low loss propagation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For this reason, waveguides are nominally fitted with microwave windows at the outer end that will not interfere with propagation but keep the elements out.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Moisture can also cause fungus build up or arcing in high power systems such as radio or radar transmitters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Moisture in waveguides can typically be prevented with silica gel, a desiccant, or slight pressurization of the waveguide cavities with dry nitrogen or argon.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Desiccant silica gel canisters may be attached with screw-on nibs and higher power systems will have pressurized tanks for maintaining pressure including leakage monitors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Arcing may also occur if there is a hole, tear or bump in the conducting walls, if transmitting at high power (usually 200 watts or more).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Waveguide plumbing is crucial for proper waveguide performance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Voltage standing waves occur when impedance mismatches in the waveguide cause energy to reflect back in the opposite direction of propagation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In addition to limiting the effective transfer of energy, these reflections can cause higher voltages in the waveguide and damage equipment.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In practice, waveguides act as the equivalent of cables for super high frequency (SHF) systems.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For such applications, it is desired to operate waveguides with only one mode propagating through the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] With rectangular waveguides, it is possible to design the waveguide such that the frequency band over which only one mode propagates is as high as 2:1 (i.e. the ratio of the upper band edge to lower band edge is two).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] With circular waveguides, the highest possible bandwidth allowing only a single mode to propagate is only 1.3601:1.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Because rectangular waveguides have a much larger bandwidth over which only a single mode can propagate, standards exist for rectangular waveguides, but not for circular waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The first condition is to allow for applications near band edges.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The second condition limits dispersion, a phenomenon in which the velocity of propagation is a function of frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] It also limits the loss per unit length.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The third condition is to avoid evanescent-wave coupling via higher order modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The fourth condition is that which allows a 2:1 operation bandwidth.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Although it is possible to have a 2:1 operating bandwidth when the height is less than half the width, having the height exactly half the width maximizes the power that can propagate inside the waveguide before dielectric breakdown occurs.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Below is a table of standard waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The waveguide name *WR* stands for *waveguide rectangular*, and the number is the inner dimension width of the waveguide in hundredths of an inch (0.01 inch = 0.254 mm) rounded to the nearest hundredth of an inch.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The waveguides inner dimensions differ slightly from those of the corresponding WM and R waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For the frequencies in the table above, the main advantage of waveguides over coaxial cables is that waveguides support propagation with lower loss.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] For lower frequencies, the waveguide dimensions become impractically large, and for higher frequencies, the dimensions become impractically small (the manufacturing tolerance becomes a significant portion of the waveguide size).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Electromagnetic waveguides are analyzed by solving Maxwell's equations, or their reduced form, the electromagnetic wave equation, with boundary conditions determined by the properties of the materials and their interfaces.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] These equations have multiple solutions, or modes, which are eigenfunctions of the equation system.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Each mode is characterized by a cutoff frequency below which the mode cannot exist in the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Waveguide propagation modes depend on the operating wavelength and polarization and the shape and size of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The longitudinal mode of a waveguide is a particular standing wave pattern formed by waves confined in the cavity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Waveguides with certain symmetries may be solved using the method of separation of variables.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Rectangular wave guides may be solved in rectangular coordinates.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Round waveguides may be solved in cylindrical coordinates.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In hollow, single conductor waveguides, TEM waves are not possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] This contrasts with two-conductor transmission lines used at lower frequencies; coaxial cable, parallel wire line and stripline, in which TEM mode is possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Additionally, the propagating modes (i.e.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] TE and TM) inside the waveguide can be mathematically expressed as the superposition of two TEM waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] The mode with the lowest cutoff frequency is termed the **dominant mode** of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] It is common to choose the size of the guide such that only this one mode can exist in the frequency band of operation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In rectangular and circular (hollow pipe) waveguides, the dominant modes are designated the TE1,0 mode and TE1,1 modes respectively.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] A *dielectric waveguide* employs a solid dielectric rod rather than a hollow pipe.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] An optical fibre is a dielectric guide designed to work at optical frequencies.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Transmission lines such as microstrip, coplanar waveguide, stripline or coaxial cable may also be considered to be waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Dielectric rod and slab waveguides are used to conduct radio waves, mostly at millimeter wave frequencies and above.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] These confine the radio waves by total internal reflection from the step in refractive index due to the change in dielectric constant at the material surface.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] At millimeter wave frequencies and above, metal is not a good conductor, so metal waveguides can have increasing attenuation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] At these wavelengths dielectric waveguides can have lower losses than metal waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] Optical fibre is a form of dielectric waveguide used at optical wavelengths.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] One difference between dielectric and metal waveguides is that at a metal surface the electromagnetic waves are tightly confined; at high frequencies the electric and magnetic fields penetrate a very short distance into the metal.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-electromagnetism] In contrast, the surface of the dielectric waveguide is an interface between two dielectrics, so the fields of the wave penetrate outside the dielectric in the form of an evanescent (non-propagating) wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A **waveguide filter** is an electronic filter constructed with waveguide technology.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguides are hollow metal conduits inside which an electromagnetic wave may be transmitted.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Filters are devices used to allow signals at some frequencies to pass (the passband), while others are rejected (the stopband).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Filters are a basic component of electronic engineering designs and have numerous applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These include selection of signals and limitation of noise.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguide filters are most useful in the microwave band of frequencies, where they are a convenient size and have low loss.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Examples of microwave filter use are found in satellite communications, telephone networks, and television broadcasting.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguide filters were developed during World War II to meet the needs of radar and electronic countermeasures, but afterwards soon found civilian applications such as use in microwave links.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Much of post-war development was concerned with reducing the bulk and weight of these filters, first by using new analysis techniques that led to elimination of unnecessary components, then by innovations such as dual-mode cavities and novel materials such as ceramic resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A particular feature of waveguide filter design concerns the mode of transmission.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Systems based on pairs of conducting wires and similar technologies have only one mode of transmission.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In waveguide systems, any number of modes are possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This can be both a disadvantage, as spurious modes frequently cause problems, and an advantage, as a dual-mode design can be much smaller than the equivalent waveguide single mode design.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The chief advantages of waveguide filters over other technologies are their ability to handle high power and their low loss.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The chief disadvantages are their bulk and cost when compared with technologies such as microstrip filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] There is a wide array of different types of waveguide filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Many of them consist of a chain of coupled resonators of some kind that can be modelled as a ladder network of LC circuits.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] One of the most common types consists of a number of coupled resonant cavities.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Even within this type, there are many subtypes, mostly differentiated by the means of coupling.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These coupling types include apertures,[w] irises,[x] and posts.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Other waveguide filter types include dielectric resonator filters, insert filters, finline filters, corrugated-waveguide filters, and stub filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A number of waveguide components have filter theory applied to their design, but their purpose is something other than to filter signals.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Such devices include impedance matching components, directional couplers, and diplexers.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These devices frequently take on the form of a filter, at least in part.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The common meaning of *waveguide*, when the term is used unqualified, is the hollow metal kind (or occasionally dielectric filled), but other waveguide technologies are possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The scope of this article is limited to the metal-conduit type.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The post-wall waveguide structure is something of a variant, but is related enough to include in this article—the wave is mostly surrounded by conducting material.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It is possible to construct waveguides out of dielectric rods, the most well known example being optical fibres.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This subject is outside the scope of the article with the exception that dielectric rod resonators are sometimes used *inside* hollow metal waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Transmission line[o] technologies such as conducting wires and microstrip can be thought of as waveguides, but are not commonly called such and are also outside the scope of this article.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In electronics, filters are used to allow signals of a certain band of frequencies to pass while blocking others.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They are a basic building block of electronic systems and have a great many applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Amongst the uses of waveguide filters are the construction of duplexers, diplexers,[d] and multiplexers; selectivity and noise limitation in receivers; and harmonic distortion suppression in transmitters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguides are metal conduits used to confine and direct radio signals.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They are usually made of brass, but aluminium and copper are also used.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Most commonly they are rectangular, but other cross-sections such as circular or elliptical are possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A waveguide filter is a filter composed of waveguide components.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It has much the same range of applications as other filter technologies in electronics and radio engineering but is very different mechanically and in principle of operation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The technology used for constructing filters is chosen to a large extent by the frequency of operation that is expected, although there is a large amount of overlap.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Low frequency applications such as audio electronics use filters composed of discrete capacitors and inductors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Somewhere in the very high frequency band, designers switch to using components made of pieces of transmission line.[p] These kinds of designs are called distributed element filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Filters made from discrete components are sometimes called lumped element filters to distinguish them.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] At still higher frequencies, the microwave bands, the design switches to waveguide filters, or sometimes a combination of waveguides and transmission lines.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguide filters have much more in common with transmission line filters than lumped element filters; they do not contain any discrete capacitors or inductors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, the waveguide design may frequently be equivalent (or approximately so) to a lumped element design.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Indeed, the design of waveguide filters frequently starts from a lumped element design and then converts the elements of that design into waveguide components.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] One of the most important differences in the operation of waveguide filters compared to transmission line designs concerns the mode of transmission of the electromagnetic wave carrying the signal.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In a transmission line, the wave is associated with electric currents on a pair of conductors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The conductors constrain the currents to be parallel to the line, and consequently both the magnetic and electric components of the electromagnetic field are perpendicular to the direction of travel of the wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This transverse mode is designated TEM[l] (transverse electromagnetic).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] On the other hand, there are infinitely many modes that any completely hollow waveguide can support, but the TEM mode is not one of them.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguide modes are designated either TE[m] (transverse electric) or TM[n] (transverse magnetic), followed by a pair of suffixes identifying the precise mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This multiplicity of modes can cause problems in waveguide filters when spurious modes are generated.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Designs are usually based on a single mode and frequently incorporate features to suppress the unwanted modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] On the other hand, advantage can be had from choosing the right mode for the application, and even sometimes making use of more than one mode at once.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Where only a single mode is in use, the waveguide can be modelled like a conducting transmission line and results from transmission line theory can be applied.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Another feature peculiar to waveguide filters is that there is a definite frequency, the cutoff frequency, below which no transmission can take place.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This means that in theory low-pass filters cannot be made in waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, designers frequently take a lumped element low-pass filter design and convert it to a waveguide implementation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The filter is consequently low-pass by design and may be considered a low-pass filter for all practical purposes if the cutoff frequency is below any frequency of interest to the application.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The waveguide cutoff frequency is a function of transmission mode, so at a given frequency, the waveguide may be usable in some modes but not others.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Likewise, the guide wavelength[h] (λg) and characteristic impedance[b] (*Z*0) of the guide at a given frequency also depend on mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The mode with the lowest cutoff frequency of all the modes is called the dominant mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Between cutoff and the next highest mode, this is the only mode it is possible to transmit, which is why it is described as dominant.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Any spurious modes generated are rapidly attenuated along the length of the guide and soon disappear.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Practical filter designs are frequently made to operate in the dominant mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In rectangular waveguide, the TE10[q] mode (shown in figure 2) is the dominant mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] There is a band of frequencies between the dominant mode cutoff and the next highest mode cutoff in which the waveguide can be operated without any possibility of generating spurious modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The next highest cutoff modes are TE20,[r] at exactly twice the TE10 mode, and TE01[s] which is also twice TE10 if the waveguide used has the commonly used aspect ratio of 2:1.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The lowest cutoff TM mode is TM11[t] (shown in figure 2) which is $\scriptstyle {\sqrt {5}}$ times the dominant mode in 2:1 waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Thus, there is an octave over which the dominant mode is free of spurious modes, although operating too close to cutoff is usually avoided because of phase distortion.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In circular waveguide, the dominant mode is TE11[u] and is shown in figure 2.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The next highest mode is TM01.[v] The range over which the dominant mode is guaranteed to be spurious-mode free is less than that in rectangular waveguide; the ratio of highest to lowest frequency is approximately 1.3 in circular waveguide, compared to 2.0 in rectangular guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Evanescent modes are modes below the cutoff frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They cannot propagate down the waveguide for any distance, dying away exponentially.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, they are important in the functioning of certain filter components such as irises and posts, described later, because energy is stored in the evanescent wave fields.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Like transmission line filters, waveguide filters always have multiple passbands, replicas of the lumped element prototype.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In most designs, only the lowest frequency passband is useful (or lowest two in the case of band-stop filters) and the rest are considered unwanted spurious artefacts.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This is an intrinsic property of the technology and cannot be designed out, although design can have some control over the frequency position of the spurious bands.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Consequently, in any given filter design, there is an upper frequency beyond which the filter will fail to carry out its function.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] For this reason, true low-pass and high-pass filters cannot exist in waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] At some high frequency there will be a spurious passband or stopband interrupting the intended function of the filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] But, similar to the situation with waveguide cutoff frequency, the filter can be designed so that the edge of the first spurious band is well above any frequency of interest.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The range of frequencies over which waveguide filters are useful is largely determined by the waveguide size needed.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] At lower frequencies the waveguide needs to be impractically large in order to keep the cutoff frequency below the operational frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] On the other hand, filters whose operating frequencies are so high that the wavelengths are sub-millimetre cannot be manufactured with normal machine shop processes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] At frequencies this high, fibre-optic technology starts to become an option.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Losses in waveguides mostly come from ohmic dissipation caused by currents induced in the waveguide walls.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Rectangular waveguide has lower loss than circular waveguide and is usually the preferred format, but the TE01 circular mode is very low loss and has applications in long-distance communications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Losses can be reduced by polishing the internal surfaces of the waveguide walls.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In some applications which require rigorous filtering, the walls are plated with a thin layer of gold or silver to improve surface conductivity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An example of such requirements is satellite applications which require low loss, high selectivity, and linear group delay from their filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] One of the main advantages of waveguide filters over TEM mode technologies is the quality of their resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Resonator quality is characterised by a parameter called Q factor, or just *Q*.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The *Q* of waveguide resonators is in the thousands, orders of magnitude higher than TEM mode resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The resistance of conductors, especially in wound inductors, limits the *Q* of TEM resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This improved *Q* leads to better performing filters in waveguides, with greater stop band rejection.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The limitation to *Q* in waveguides comes mostly from the ohmic losses in the walls described earlier, but silver plating the internal walls can more than double *Q*.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguides have good power handling capability, which leads to filter applications in radar.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Despite the performance advantages of waveguide filters, microstrip is often the preferred technology due to its low cost.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This is especially true for consumer items and the lower microwave frequencies.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Microstrip circuits can be manufactured by cheap printed circuit technology, and when integrated on the same printed board as other circuit blocks they incur little additional cost.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The idea of a waveguide for electromagnetic waves was first suggested by Lord Rayleigh in 1897.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Rayleigh proposed that a coaxial transmission line could have the centre conductor removed, and waves would still propagate down the inside of the remaining cylindrical conductor despite there no longer being a complete electrical circuit of conductors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] He described this in terms of the wave reflecting repeatedly off the internal wall of the outer conductor in a zig-zag fashion as it progressed down the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Rayleigh was also the first to realise that there was a critical wavelength, the cutoff wavelength, proportional to the cylinder diameter, above which wave propagation is not possible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, interest in waveguides waned because lower frequencies were more suitable for long-distance radio communication.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Rayleigh's results were forgotten for a time and had to be rediscovered by others in the 1930s when interest in microwaves revived.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguides were first developed, in a circular form, by George Clark Southworth and J.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The first analogue filter design which went beyond a simple single resonator was created by George Ashley Campbell in 1910 and marked the beginning of filter theory.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Campbell's filter was a lumped-element design of capacitors and inductors suggested by his work with loading coils.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Otto Zobel and others quickly developed this further.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Development of distributed element filters began in the years before World War II.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A major paper on the subject was published by Mason and Sykes in 1937; a patent filed by Mason in 1927 may contain the first published filter design using distributed elements.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Mason and Sykes' work was focused on the formats of coaxial cable and balanced pairs of wires, but other researchers later applied the principles to waveguides as well.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Much development on waveguide filters was carried out during World War II driven by the filtering needs of radar and electronic countermeasures.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A good deal of this was at the MIT Radiation Laboratory (Rad Lab), but other laboratories in the US and the UK were also involved such as the Telecommunications Research Establishment in the UK.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Amongst the well-known scientists and engineers at Rad Lab were Julian Schwinger, Nathan Marcuvitz, Edward Mills Purcell, and Hans Bethe.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Bethe was only at Rad Lab a short time but produced his aperture theory while there.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Aperture theory is important for waveguide cavity filters, which were first developed at Rad Lab.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Their work was published after the war in 1948 and includes an early description of dual-mode cavities by Fano and Lawson.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Theoretical work following the war included the commensurate line theory of Paul Richards.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Kuroda published the transformations known as Kuroda's identities.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These made Richard's work more usable in unbalanced and waveguide formats by eliminating the problematic series connected elements, but it was some time before Kuroda's Japanese work became widely known in the English speaking world.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Another theoretical development was the network synthesis filter approach of Wilhelm Cauer in which he used the Chebyshev approximation to determine element values.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Cauer's work was largely developed during World War II (Cauer was killed towards the end of it), but could not be widely published until hostilities ended.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] While Cauer's work concerns lumped elements, it is of some importance to waveguide filters; the Chebyshev filter, a special case of Cauer's synthesis, is widely used as a prototype filter for waveguide designs.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Designs in the 1950s started with a lumped element prototype (a technique still in use today), arriving after various transformations at the desired filter in a waveguide form.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] At the time, this approach was yielding fractional bandwidths no more than about ⁠1/5⁠.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In 1957, Leo Young at Stanford Research Institute published a method for designing filters which *started* with a distributed element prototype, the stepped impedance prototype.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This filter was based on quarter-wave impedance transformers of various widths and was able to produce designs with bandwidths up to an octave (a fractional bandwidth of ⁠2/3⁠).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Young's paper specifically addresses directly coupled cavity resonators, but the procedure can equally be applied to other directly coupled resonator types.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The first published account of a cross-coupled filter is due to John R.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A cross-coupled filter is one in which resonators that are not immediately adjacent are coupled.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The additional degrees of freedom thus provided allow the designer to create filters with improved performance, or, alternatively, with fewer resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] One version of Pierce's filter, shown in figure 3, uses circular waveguide cavity resonators to link between rectangular guide cavity resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This principle was not at first much used by waveguide filter designers, but it was used extensively by mechanical filter designers in the 1960s, particularly R.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The initial non-military application of waveguide filters was in the microwave links used by telecommunications companies to provide the backbone of their networks.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These links were also used by other industries with large, fixed networks, notably television broadcasters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Such applications were part of large capital investment programs.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They are now also used in satellite communications systems.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The need for frequency-independent delay in satellite applications led to more research into the waveguide incarnation of cross-coupled filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Previously, satellite communications systems used a separate component for delay equalisation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The additional degrees of freedom obtained from cross-coupled filters held out the possibility of designing a flat delay into a filter without compromising other performance parameters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A component that simultaneously functioned as both filter and equaliser would save valuable weight and space.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The needs of satellite communication also drove research into the more exotic resonator modes in the 1970s.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Of particular prominence in this respect is the work of E.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Young, who investigated better modes for the 12-14 GHz band when this began to be used for satellites in the mid-1970s.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Another space-saving innovation was the dielectric resonator, which can be used in other filter formats as well as waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The first use of these in a filter was by S.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Cohn in 1965, using titanium dioxide as the dielectric material.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Dielectric resonators used in the 1960s, however, had very poor temperature coefficients, typically 500 times worse than a mechanical resonator made of invar, which led to instability of filter parameters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Dielectric materials of the time with better temperature coefficients had too low a dielectric constant to be useful for space saving.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This changed with the introduction of ceramic resonators with very low temperature coefficients in the 1970s.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The first of these was from Massé and Pucel using barium tetratitanate at Raytheon in 1972.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Further improvements were reported in 1979 by Bell Labs and Murata Manufacturing.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Bell Labs' barium nonatitanate resonator had a dielectric constant of 40 and *Q* of 5000–10,000 at 2-7 GHz.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An alternative approach to designing smaller waveguide filters was provided by the use of non-propagating evanescent modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Jaynes and Edson proposed evanescent mode waveguide filters in the late 1950s.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Methods for designing these filters were created by Craven and Young in 1966.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Since then, evanescent mode waveguide filters have seen successful use where waveguide size or weight are important considerations.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A relatively recent technology being used inside hollow-metal-waveguide filters is finline, a kind of planar dielectric waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Finline was first described by Paul Meier in 1972.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Multiplexers were first described by Fano and Lawson in 1948.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Pierce was the first to describe multiplexers with contiguous passbands.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Multiplexing using directional filters was invented by Seymour Cohn and Frank Coale in the 1950s.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Multiplexers with compensating immittance resonators at each junction are largely the work of E.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This technique is still sometimes used, but the modern availability of computing power has led to the more common use of synthesis techniques which can directly produce matching filters without the need for these additional resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Wenzel discovered that filters which were singly terminated,[k] rather than the usual doubly terminated, were complementary—exactly what was needed for a diplexer.[c] Wenzel was inspired by the lectures of circuit theorist Ernst Guillemin.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Multi-channel, multi-octave multiplexers were investigated by Harold Schumacher at Microphase Corporation, and his results were published in 1976.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The principle that multiplexer filters may be matched when joined together by modifying the first few elements, thus doing away with the compensating resonators, was discovered accidentally by E.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Curly around 1968 when he mistuned a diplexer.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A formal theory for this was provided by J.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Rhodes in 1976 and generalised to multiplexers by Rhodes and Ralph Levy in 1979.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] From the 1980s, planar technologies, especially microstrip, have tended to replace other technologies used for constructing filters and multiplexers, especially in products aimed at the consumer market.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The recent innovation of post-wall waveguide allows waveguide designs to be implemented on a flat substrate with low-cost manufacturing techniques similar to those used for microstrip.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waveguide filter designs frequently consist of two different components repeated a number of times.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Typically, one component is a resonator or discontinuity with a lumped circuit equivalent of an inductor, capacitor, or LC resonant circuit.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Often, the filter type will take its name from the style of this component.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These components are spaced apart by a second component, a length of guide which acts as an impedance transformer.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The impedance transformers have the effect of making alternate instances of the first component appear to be a different impedance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The net result is a lumped element equivalent circuit of a ladder network.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Lumped element filters are commonly ladder topology, and such a circuit is a typical starting point for waveguide filter designs.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Typically, waveguide components are resonators, and the equivalent circuit would be LC resonators instead of the capacitors and inductors shown, but circuits like figure 4 are still used as prototype filters with the use of a band-pass or band-stop transformation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Filter performance parameters, such as stopband rejection and rate of transition between passband and stopband, are improved by adding more components and thus increasing the length of the filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Where the components are repeated identically, the filter is an image parameter filter design, and performance is enhanced simply by adding more identical elements.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This approach is typically used in filter designs which use a large number of closely spaced elements such as the waffle-iron filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] For designs where the elements are more widely spaced, better results can be obtained using a network synthesis filter design, such as the common Chebyshev filter and Butterworth filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In this approach the circuit elements do not all have the same value, and consequently the components are not all the same dimensions.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Furthermore, if the design is enhanced by adding more components then all the element values must be calculated again from scratch.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In general, there will be no common values between the two instances of the design.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Chebyshev waveguide filters are used where the filtering requirements are rigorous, such as satellite applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An impedance transformer is a device which makes an impedance at its output port appear as a different impedance at its input port.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In waveguide, this device is simply a short length of waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Especially useful is the quarter-wave impedance transformer which has a length of λg/4.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This device can turn capacitances into inductances and vice versa.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It also has the useful property of turning shunt-connected elements into series-connected elements and vice versa.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Series-connected elements are otherwise difficult to implement in waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Many waveguide filter components work by introducing a sudden change, a discontinuity, to the transmission properties of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Such discontinuities are equivalent to lumped impedance elements placed at that point.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This arises in the following way: the discontinuity causes a partial reflection of the transmitted wave back down the guide in the opposite direction, the ratio of the two being known as the reflection coefficient.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This is entirely analogous to a reflection on a transmission line where there is an established relationship between reflection coefficient and the impedance that caused the reflection.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This impedance must be reactive, that is, it must be a capacitance or an inductance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It cannot be a resistance since no energy has been absorbed—it is all either transmitted onward or reflected.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Examples of components with this function include irises, stubs, and posts, all described later in this article under the filter types in which they occur.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An impedance step is an example of a device introducing a discontinuity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It is achieved by a step change in the physical dimensions of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This results in a step change in the characteristic impedance of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The step can be in either the E-plane[f] (change of height[j]) or the H-plane[g] (change of width[i]) of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A basic component of waveguide filters is the cavity resonator.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This consists of a short length of waveguide blocked at both ends.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Waves trapped inside the resonator are reflected back and forth between the two ends.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A given geometry of cavity will resonate at a characteristic frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The resonance effect can be used to selectively pass certain frequencies.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Their use in a filter structure requires that some of the wave is allowed to pass out of one cavity into another through a coupling structure.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, if the opening in the resonator is kept small then a valid design approach is to design the cavity as if it were completely closed and errors will be minimal.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A number of different coupling mechanisms are used in different classes of filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The nomenclature for modes in a cavity introduces a third index, for example TE011.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The first two indices describe the wave travelling up and down the length of the cavity, that is, they are the transverse mode numbers as for modes in a waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The third index describes the longitudinal mode caused by the interference pattern of the forward travelling and reflected waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The third index is equal to the number of half wavelengths down the length of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The most common modes used are the dominant modes: TE101 in rectangular waveguide, and TE111 in circular waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] TE011 circular mode is used where very low loss (hence high *Q*) is required but cannot be used in a dual-mode filter because it is circularly symmetric.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Better modes for rectangular waveguide in dual-mode filters are TE103 and TE105.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, even better is the TE113 circular waveguide mode which can achieve a *Q* of 16,000 at 12 GHz.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Tuning screws are screws inserted into resonant cavities which can be adjusted externally to the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They provide fine tuning of the resonant frequency by inserting more, or less thread into the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Examples can be seen in the post filter of figure 1: each cavity has a tuning screw secured with jam nuts and thread-locking compound.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] For screws inserted only a small distance, the equivalent circuit is a shunt capacitor, increasing in value as the screw is inserted.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, when the screw has been inserted a distance λ/4 it resonates equivalent to a series LC circuit.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Inserting it further causes the impedance to change from capacitive to inductive, that is, the arithmetic sign changes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An iris is a thin metal plate across the waveguide with one or more holes in it.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It is used to couple together two lengths of waveguide and is a means of introducing a discontinuity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Some of the possible geometries of irises are shown in figure 5.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An iris which reduces the width of a rectangular waveguide has an equivalent circuit of a shunt inductance, whereas one which restricts the height is equivalent to a shunt capacitance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An iris which restricts both directions is equivalent to a parallel LC resonant circuit.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A series LC circuit can be formed by spacing the conducting portion of the iris away from the walls of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Narrowband filters frequently use irises with small holes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These are always inductive regardless of the shape of the hole or its position on the iris.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Circular holes are simple to machine, but elongated holes, or holes in the shape of a cross, are advantageous in allowing the selection of a particular mode of coupling.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Irises are a form of discontinuity and work by exciting evanescent higher modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Vertical edges are parallel to the electric field (E field) and excite TE modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The stored energy in TE modes is predominately in the magnetic field (H field), and consequently the lumped equivalent of this structure is an inductor.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Horizontal edges are parallel to the H field and excite TM modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In this case the stored energy is predominately in the E field and the lumped equivalent is a capacitor.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It is fairly simple to make irises that are mechanically adjustable.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A thin plate of metal can be pushed in and out of a narrow slot in the side of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The iris construction is sometimes chosen for this ability to make a variable component.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] An iris-coupled filter consists of a cascade of impedance transformers in the form of waveguide resonant cavities coupled together by irises.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In high power applications capacitive irises are avoided.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The reduction in height of the waveguide (the direction of the E field) causes the electric field strength across the gap to increase and arcing (or dielectric breakdown if the waveguide is filled with an insulator) will occur at a lower power than it would otherwise.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Posts are conducting bars, usually circular, fixed internally across the height of the waveguide and are another means of introducing a discontinuity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A thin post has an equivalent circuit of a shunt inductor.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A row of posts can be viewed as a form of inductive iris.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A post filter consists of several rows of posts across the width of the waveguide which separate the waveguide into resonant cavities as shown in figure 7.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Differing numbers of posts can be used in each row to achieve varying values of inductance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The filter operates in the same way as the iris-coupled filter but differs in the method of construction.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It consists of an insulated substrate pierced with two rows of conducting posts which stand in for the side walls of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The top and bottom of the substrate are covered with conducting sheets making this a similar construction to the triplate format.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The existing manufacturing techniques of printed circuit board or low temperature co-fired ceramic can be used to make post-wall waveguide circuits.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This format naturally lends itself to waveguide post filter designs.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A dual-mode filter is a kind of resonant cavity filter, but in this case each cavity is used to provide two resonators by employing two modes (two polarizations), so halving the volume of the filter for a given order.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This improvement in size of the filter is a major advantage in aircraft avionics and space applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] High quality filters in these applications can require many cavities which occupy significant space.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Dielectric resonators are pieces of dielectric material inserted into the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They are usually cylindrical since these can be made without machining but other shapes have been used.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] They can be made with a hole through the centre which is used to secure them to the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] There is no field at the centre when the TE011 circular mode is used so the hole has no adverse effect.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The resonators can be mounted coaxial to the waveguide, but usually they are mounted transversally across the width as shown in figure 8.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The latter arrangement allows the resonators to be tuned by inserting a screw through the wall of the waveguide into the centre hole of the resonator.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] When dielectric resonators are made from a high permittivity material, such as one of the barium titanates, they have an important space saving advantage compared to cavity resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, they are much more prone to spurious modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In high-power applications, metal layers may be built into the resonators to conduct heat away since dielectric materials tend to have low thermal conductivity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The resonators can be coupled together with irises or impedance transformers.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Alternatively, they can be placed in a stub-like side-housing and coupled through a small aperture.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In **insert filters** one or more metal sheets are placed longitudinally down the length of the waveguide as shown in figure 9.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These sheets have holes punched in them to form resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The air dielectric gives these resonators a high *Q*.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Several parallel inserts may be used in the same length of waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] More compact resonators may be achieved with a thin sheet of dielectric material and printed metallisation instead of holes in metal sheets at the cost of a lower resonator *Q*.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Finline is a different kind of waveguide technology in which waves in a thin strip of dielectric are constrained by two strips of metallisation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] There are a number of possible topological arrangements of the dielectric and metal strips.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Finline is a variation of slot-waveguide but in the case of finline the whole structure is enclosed in a metal shield.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This has the advantage that, like hollow metal waveguide, no power is lost by radiation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Finline filters can be made by printing a metallisation pattern on to a sheet of dielectric material and then inserting the sheet into the E-plane of a hollow metal waveguide much as is done with insert filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The metal waveguide forms the shield for the finline waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Resonators are formed by metallising a pattern on to the dielectric sheet.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] More complex patterns than the simple insert filter of figure 9 are easily achieved because the designer does not have to consider the effect on mechanical support of removing metal.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This complexity does not add to the manufacturing costs since the number of processes needed does not change when more elements are added to the design.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Finline designs are less sensitive to manufacturing tolerances than insert filters and have wide bandwidths.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It is possible to design filters that operate internally entirely in evanescent modes.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This has space saving advantages because the filter waveguide, which often forms the housing of the filter, does not need to be large enough to support propagation of the dominant mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Typically, an evanescent mode filter consists of a length of waveguide smaller than the waveguide feeding the input and output ports.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In some designs this may be folded to achieve a more compact filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Tuning screws are inserted at specific intervals along the waveguide producing equivalent lumped capacitances at those points.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In more recent designs the screws are replaced with dielectric inserts.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] These capacitors resonate with the preceding length of evanescent mode waveguide which has the equivalent circuit of an inductor, thus producing a filtering action.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Energy from many different evanescent modes is stored in the field around each of these capacitive discontinuities.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, the design is such that only the dominant mode reaches the output port; the other modes decay much more rapidly between the capacitors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The waffle-iron filter is a variant of the corrugated-waveguide filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] It has similar properties to that filter with the additional advantage that spurious TE20 and TE30 modes are suppressed.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In the waffle-iron filter, channels are cut through the ridges longitudinally down the filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This leaves a matrix of teeth protruding internally from the top and bottom surfaces of the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] This pattern of teeth resembles a waffle iron, hence the name of the filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A stub is a short length of waveguide connected to some point in the filter at one end and short-circuited at the other end.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Open-circuited stubs are also theoretically possible, but an implementation in waveguide is not practical because electromagnetic energy would be emitted from the open end of the stub, resulting in high losses.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] Stubs are a kind of resonator, and the lumped element equivalent is an LC resonant circuit.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] However, over a narrow band, stubs can be viewed as an impedance transformer.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The short-circuit is transformed into either an inductance or a capacitance depending on the stub length.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] A waveguide stub filter is made by placing one or more stubs along the length of a waveguide, usually λg/4 apart, as shown in figure 12.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] The ends of the stubs are blanked off to short-circuit them.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] When the short-circuited stubs are λg/4 long the filter will be a band-stop filter and the stubs will have a lumped-element approximate equivalent circuit of parallel resonant circuits connected in series with the line.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] When the stubs are λg/2 long, the filter will be a band-pass filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p01] In this case the lumped-element equivalent is series LC resonant circuits in series with the line.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] There are many applications of filters whose design objectives are something other than rejection or passing of certain frequencies.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Frequently, a simple device that is intended to work over only a narrow band or just one spot frequency will not look much like a filter design.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] However, a broadband design for the same item requires many more elements and the design takes on the nature of a filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Amongst the more common applications of this kind in waveguide are impedance matching networks, directional couplers, power dividers, power combiners, and diplexers.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Other possible applications include multiplexers, demultiplexers, negative-resistance amplifiers, and time-delay networks.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A simple method of impedance matching is stub matching with a single stub.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] However, a single stub will only produce a perfect match at one particular frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This technique is therefore only suitable for narrow band applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] To widen the bandwidth multiple stubs may be used, and the structure then takes on the form of a stub filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The design proceeds as if it were a filter except that a different parameter is optimised.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In a frequency filter typically the parameter optimised is stopband rejection, passband attenuation, steepness of transition, or some compromise between these.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In a matching network the parameter optimised is the impedance match.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The function of the device does not require a restriction of bandwidth, but the designer is nevertheless forced to choose a bandwidth because of the *structure* of the device.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Stubs are not the only format of filter than can be used.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In principle, any filter structure could be applied to impedance matching, but some will result in more practical designs than others.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A frequent format used for impedance matching in waveguide is the stepped impedance filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] An example can be seen in the duplexer[e] pictured in figure 13.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Directional couplers, power splitters, and power combiners are all essentially the same type of device, at least when implemented with passive components.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A directional coupler splits a small amount of power from the main line to a third port.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A more strongly coupled, but otherwise identical, device may be called a power splitter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] One that couples exactly half the power to the third port (a 3 dB coupler) is the maximum coupling achievable without reversing the functions of the ports.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Many designs of power splitter can be used in reverse, whereupon they become power combiners.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A simple form of directional coupler is two parallel transmission lines coupled together over a λ/4 length.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This design is limited because the electrical length of the coupler will only be λ/4 at one specific frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Coupling will be a maximum at this frequency and fall away on either side.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Similar to the impedance matching case, this can be improved by using multiple elements, resulting in a filter-like structure.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A waveguide analogue of this coupled lines approach is the Bethe-hole directional coupler in which two parallel waveguides are stacked on top of each other and a hole provided for coupling.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] To produce a wideband design, multiple holes are used along the guides as shown in figure 14 and a filter design applied.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] It is not only the coupled-line design that suffers from being narrow band, all simple designs of waveguide coupler depend on frequency in some way.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] For instance the rat-race coupler (which can be implemented directly in waveguide) works on a completely different principle but still relies on certain lengths being exact in terms of λ.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A diplexer is a device used to combine two signals occupying different frequency bands into a single signal.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This is usually to enable two signals to be transmitted simultaneously on the same communications channel, or to allow transmitting on one frequency while receiving on another.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] (This specific use of a diplexer is called a duplexer.) The same device can be used to separate the signals again at the far end of the channel.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The need for filtering to separate the signals while receiving is fairly self-evident but it is also required even when combining two transmitted signals.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Without filtering, some of the power from source A will be sent towards source B instead of the combined output.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This will have the detrimental effects of losing a portion of the input power and loading source A with the output impedance of source B thus causing mismatch.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] These problems could be overcome with the use of a 3 dB directional coupler, but as explained in the previous section, a wideband design requires a filter design for directional couplers as well.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Two widely spaced narrowband signals can be diplexed by joining together the outputs of two appropriate band-pass filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Steps need to be taken to prevent the filters from coupling to each other when they are at resonance which would cause degradation of their performance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This can be achieved by appropriate spacing.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] For instance, if the filters are of the iris-coupled type then the iris nearest to the filter junction of filter A is placed λgb/4 from the junction where λgb is the guide wavelength in the passband of filter B.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Likewise, the nearest iris of filter B is placed λga/4 from the junction.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This works because when filter A is at resonance, filter B is in its stopband and only loosely coupled and vice versa.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] An alternative arrangement is to have each filter joined to a main waveguide at separate junctions.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A decoupling resonator is placed λg/4 from the junction of each filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This can be in the form of a short-circuited stub tuned to the resonant frequency of that filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This arrangement can be extended to multiplexers with any number of bands.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] For diplexers dealing with contiguous passbands proper account of the crossover characteristics of filters needs to be considered in the design.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] An especially common case of this is where the diplexer is used to split the entire spectrum into low and high bands.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Here a low-pass and a high-pass filter are used instead of band-pass filters.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The synthesis techniques used here can equally be applied to narrowband multiplexers and largely remove the need for decoupling resonators.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A directional filter is a device that combines the functions of a directional coupler and a diplexer.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] As it is based on a directional coupler it is essentially a four-port device, but like directional couplers, port 4 is commonly permanently terminated internally.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Power entering port 1 exits port 3 after being subject to some filtering function (usually band-pass).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The remaining power exits port 2, and since no power is absorbed or reflected this will be the exact complement of the filtering function at port 2, in this case band-stop.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In reverse, power entering ports 2 and 3 is combined at port 1, but now the power from the signals rejected by the filter is absorbed in the load at port 4.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Figure 15 shows one possible waveguide implementation of a directional filter.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Two rectangular waveguides operating in the dominant TE10 mode provide the four ports.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] These are joined together by a circular waveguide operating in the circular TE11 mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The circular waveguide contains an iris coupled filter with as many irises as needed to produce the required filter response.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] An opening in a wall of a waveguide or barrier between sections of waveguide through which electromagnetic radiation can propagate.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] , of a waveguide for a particular mode is defined as the ratio of the transverse electric field to the transverse magnetic field of a wave travelling in one direction down the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] is the guide wavelength, and λ is the wavelength when unrestricted by the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] , where κ is the dielectric constant of the material, and λ replaced by the unrestricted wavelength in the dielectric medium.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In some treatments what is called characteristic impedance here is called the wave impedance, and characteristic impedance is defined as proportional to it by some constant.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A diplexer combines or separates two signals occupying different passbands.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A duplexer combines or splits two signals travelling in opposite directions, or of differing polarizations (which may also be in different passbands as well).
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The E-plane is the plane lying in the direction of the transverse electric field, that is, vertically along the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] , is the wavelength measured longitudinally down the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] where λ is the wavelength the wave would have if unrestricted by the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] ), that is, horizontally along the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Of a rectangular guide, these refer respectively to the small and large internal dimensions of its cross-section.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The polarization of the E-field of the dominant mode is parallel to the height.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A conducting plate fitted transversally across the waveguide with a, usually large, aperture.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A doubly terminated filter (the normal case) is one where the generator and load, connected to the input and output ports respectively, have impedances matching the filter characteristic impedance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A singly terminated filter has a matching load, but is driven either by a low impedance voltage source or a high impedance current source.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Transverse electromagnetic mode, a transmission mode where all the electric field and all the magnetic field are perpendicular to the direction of travel of the electromagnetic wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] This is the usual mode of transmission in pairs of conductors.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Transverse electric mode, one of a number of modes in which all the electric field, but not all the magnetic field, is perpendicular to the direction of travel of the electromagnetic wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] They are designated H modes in some sources because these modes have a longitudinal magnetic component.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] The first index indicates the number of half wavelengths of field across the width of the waveguide, and the second index indicates the number of half wavelengths across the height.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Properly, the indices should be separated with a comma, but usually they are run together, as mode numbers in double figures rarely need to be considered.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Some modes specifically mentioned in this article are listed below.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] All modes are for rectangular waveguide unless otherwise stated.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A mode with one half-wave of electric field across the height of the guide and uniform electric field (zero half-waves) across the width of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A mode with one half-wave of electric field across the width of the guide and uniform electric field across the height of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A mode with two half-waves of electric field across the width of the guide and uniform electric field across the height of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A mode with one full-wave of electric field around the circumference of the guide and one half-wave of electric field along a radius.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] Transverse magnetic mode, one of a number of modes in which all the magnetic field, but not all the electric field, is perpendicular to the direction of travel of the electromagnetic wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] They are designated E modes in some sources because these modes have a longitudinal electric component.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] See TE mode for a description of the meaning of the indices.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A mode with one half-wave of magnetic field across the width of the guide and one half-wave of magnetic field across the height of the guide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A mode with uniform magnetic field around the circumference of the guide and one half-wave of magnetic field along a radius.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] A transmission line is a signal transmission medium consisting of a pair of electrical conductors separated from each other, or one conductor and a common return path.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In some treatments waveguides are considered to be within the class of transmission lines, with which they have much in common.
[src:waveguides/waveguide-filter-p02] In this article waveguides are not included so that the two types of medium can more easily be distinguished and referred.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] A **waveguide** is a structure that guides waves by restricting the direction of transmission of energy.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Common types of waveguides include acoustic waveguides which direct sound, optical waveguides which direct light, and radio-frequency waveguides which direct electromagnetic waves other than visible, or near visible, light, like radio waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Without the physical constraint of a waveguide, waves would expand into three-dimensional space and their intensities would decrease according to the inverse square law.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] There are different types of waveguides for different types of waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The original and most common meaning is a hollow conductive metal pipe used to carry high frequency radio waves, particularly microwaves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Dielectric waveguides are used at higher radio frequencies, and transparent dielectric waveguides and optical fibers serve as waveguides for light.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] In acoustics, air ducts and horns are used as waveguides for sound in musical instruments and loudspeakers, and specially-shaped metal rods conduct ultrasonic waves in ultrasonic machining.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The geometry of a waveguide reflects its function; in addition to more common types that channel the wave in one dimension, there are two-dimensional slab waveguides which confine waves to two dimensions.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The frequency of the transmitted wave also dictates the size of a waveguide: each waveguide has a cutoff wavelength determined by its size and will not conduct waves of greater wavelength; an optical fiber that guides light will not transmit microwaves which have a much larger wavelength.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Some naturally occurring structures can also act as waveguides.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The SOFAR channel layer in the ocean can guide the sound of whale song across enormous distances.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Any shape of waveguide can support EM waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] However, irregular shapes are difficult to analyse.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Commonly used waveguides are rectangular or circular in cross-section.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The uses of waveguides for transmitting signals were known even before the term was coined.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The phenomenon of sound waves guided through a taut wire have been known for a long time, as well as sound through a hollow pipe such as a cave or medical stethoscope.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Other uses of waveguides are in transmitting power between the components of a system such as radio, radar or optical devices.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Waveguides are the fundamental principle of guided wave testing (GWT), one of the many methods of non-destructive evaluation.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The first structure for guiding waves was proposed by J.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Thomson in 1893, and was first experimentally tested by Oliver Lodge in 1894.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The first mathematical analysis of electromagnetic waves in a metal cylinder was performed by Lord Rayleigh in 1897.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] For sound waves, Lord Rayleigh published a full mathematical analysis of propagation modes in his seminal work, "The Theory of Sound".
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Jagadish Chandra Bose researched millimeter wavelengths using waveguides, and in 1897 described to the Royal Institution in London his research carried out in Kolkata.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The study of dielectric waveguides (such as optical fibers, see below) began as early as the 1920s, by several people, most famous of which are Rayleigh, Sommerfeld and Debye.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Optical fiber began to receive special attention in the 1960s due to its importance to the communications industry.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The development of radio communication initially occurred at the lower frequencies because these could be more easily propagated over large distances.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The long wavelengths made these frequencies unsuitable for use in hollow metal waveguides because of the impractically large diameter tubes required.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Consequently, research into hollow metal waveguides stalled and the work of Lord Rayleigh was forgotten for a time and had to be rediscovered by others.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Practical investigations resumed in the 1930s by George C.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Southworth at first took the theory from papers on waves in dielectric rods because the work of Lord Rayleigh was unknown to him.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] This misled him somewhat; some of his experiments failed because he was not aware of the phenomenon of waveguide cutoff frequency already found in Lord Rayleigh's work.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Serious theoretical work was taken up by John R.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] This work led to the discovery that for the TE01 mode in circular waveguide losses go down with frequency and at one time this was a serious contender for the format for long-distance telecommunications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The importance of radar in World War II gave a great impetus to waveguide research, at least on the Allied side.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The magnetron, developed in 1940 by John Randall and Harry Boot at the University of Birmingham in the United Kingdom, provided a good power source and made microwave radar feasible.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The most important centre of US research was at the Radiation Laboratory (Rad Lab) at MIT but many others took part in the US, and in the UK such as the Telecommunications Research Establishment.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The head of the Fundamental Development Group at Rad Lab was Edward Mills Purcell.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] His researchers included Julian Schwinger, Nathan Marcuvitz, Carol Gray Montgomery, and Robert H.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Much of the Rad Lab work concentrated on finding lumped element models of waveguide structures so that components in waveguide could be analysed with standard circuit theory.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Hans Bethe was also briefly at Rad Lab, but while there he produced his small aperture theory which proved important for waveguide cavity filters, first developed at Rad Lab.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The German side, on the other hand, largely ignored the potential of waveguides in radar until very late in the war.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] So much so that when radar parts from a downed British plane were sent to Siemens & Halske for analysis, even though they were recognised as microwave components, their purpose could not be identified.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] German academics were even allowed to continue publicly publishing their research in this field because it was not felt to be important.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Immediately after World War II waveguide was the technology of choice in the microwave field.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] However, it has some problems; it is bulky, expensive to produce, and the cutoff frequency effect makes it difficult to produce wideband devices.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Ridged waveguide can increase bandwidth beyond an octave, but a better solution is to use a technology working in TEM mode (that is, non-waveguide) such as coaxial conductors since TEM does not have a cutoff frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] A shielded rectangular conductor can also be used and this has certain manufacturing advantages over coax and can be seen as the forerunner of the planar technologies (stripline and microstrip).
[src:waveguides/waveguide] However, planar technologies really started to take off when printed circuits were introduced.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] These methods are significantly cheaper than waveguide and have largely taken its place in most bands.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] However, waveguide is still favoured in the higher microwave bands from around Ku band upwards.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] A propagation mode in a waveguide is one solution of the wave equations, or, in other words, the form of the wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Due to the constraints of the boundary conditions, there are only limited frequencies and forms for the wave function which can propagate in the waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The lowest frequency in which a certain mode can propagate is the cutoff frequency of that mode.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The mode with the lowest cutoff frequency is the fundamental mode of the waveguide, and its cutoff frequency is the waveguide cutoff frequency.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Propagation modes are computed by solving the Helmholtz equation alongside a set of boundary conditions depending on the geometrical shape and materials bounding the region.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The usual assumption for infinitely long uniform waveguides allows us to assume a propagating form for the wave, i.e. stating that every field component has a known dependency on the propagation direction (i.e. z ).
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Then, every unknown field is forced to have a form like $U(x,y,z)={\hat {U}}(x,y)e^{-\gamma z}$ , where the $\gamma$ term represents the propagation constant (still unknown) along the direction along which the waveguide extends to infinity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The Helmholtz equation can be rewritten to accommodate such form and the resulting equality needs to be solved for $\gamma$ and ${\hat {U}}(x,y)$ , yielding in the end an eigenvalue equation for $\gamma$ and a corresponding eigenfunction ${\hat {U}}(x,y)_{\gamma }$ for each solution of the former.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The propagation constant $\gamma$ of the guided wave is complex, in general.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] For a lossless case, the propagation constant might be found to take on either real or imaginary values, depending on the chosen solution of the eigenvalue equation and on the angular frequency $\omega$ .
[src:waveguides/waveguide] In circuit theory, the impedance is a generalization of electrical resistance in the case of alternating current, and is measured in ohms ( $\Omega$ ).
[src:waveguides/waveguide] A waveguide in circuit theory is described by a transmission line having a length and characteristic impedance.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] In other words, the impedance indicates the ratio of voltage to current of the circuit component (in this case a waveguide) during propagation of the wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Impedance matching is important when components of an electric circuit are connected (waveguide to antenna for example): The impedance ratio determines how much of the wave is transmitted forward and how much is reflected.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] In connecting a waveguide to an antenna a complete transmission is usually required, so an effort is made to match their impedances.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] An impedance mismatch creates a reflected wave, which added to the incoming waves creates a standing wave.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Waveguides can be constructed to carry waves over a wide portion of the electromagnetic spectrum, but are especially useful in the microwave and optical frequency ranges.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Depending on the frequency, they can be constructed from either conductive or dielectric materials.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Waveguides are used for transferring both power and communication signals.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Waveguides used at optical frequencies are typically dielectric waveguides, structures in which a dielectric material with high permittivity, and thus high index of refraction, is surrounded by a material with lower permittivity.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The structure guides optical waves by total internal reflection.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] An example of an optical waveguide is optical fiber.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Other types of optical waveguide are also used, including photonic-crystal fiber, which guides waves by any of several distinct mechanisms.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Guides in the form of a hollow tube with a highly reflective inner surface have also been used as light pipes for illumination applications.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The inner surfaces may be polished metal, or may be covered with a multilayer film that guides light by Bragg reflection (this is a special case of a photonic-crystal fiber).
[src:waveguides/waveguide] One can also use small prisms around the pipe which reflect light via total internal reflection —such confinement is necessarily imperfect, however, since total internal reflection can never truly guide light within a *lower*-index core (in the prism case, some light leaks out at the prism corners).
[src:waveguides/waveguide] An *acoustic waveguide* is a physical structure for guiding sound waves.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Sound in an acoustic waveguide behaves like electromagnetic waves on a transmission line.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Waves on a string, like the ones in a tin can telephone, are a simple example of an acoustic waveguide.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Another example are pressure waves in the pipes of an organ.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] The term *acoustic waveguide* is also used to describe elastic waves guided in micro-scale devices, like those employed in piezoelectric delay lines and in stimulated Brillouin scattering.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] A waveguide (or tube) impose a boundary condition on the wave equation such that the wave function must be equal to zero on the boundary and that the allowed region is finite in all but one dimension.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] An infinitely long cylinder is an example.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Mathematically, any tube with a bulge, where the width of the tube increases, admits at least one non-propagating bound state.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Using the variational principles, Jeffrey Goldstone and Robert Jaffe have shown a tube of constant width with a twist admits a bound state.
[src:waveguides/waveguide] Sound synthesis uses digital delay lines as computational elements to simulate wave propagation in tubes of wind instruments and the vibrating strings of string instruments.
